  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Petrie Terrace is Brisbane's smallest inner-city suburb by area, a compact grid of workers' cottages and timber-and-tin homes sitting between Caxton Street, the Roma Street Parkland and Suncorp Stadium. The character of the suburb is unusually consistent: heritage protections have prevented the kind of redevelopment that has reshaped neighbouring suburbs, and what is here in 2026 is largely what has been here for a century. Sellers in Petrie Terrace are operating in a market where scarcity is genuinely structural, where the buyer pool is small but focused, and where presentation and pricing have to respect the suburb's particular character.</p>

      <p>The suburb's appeal to buyers is direct. CBD walkability, restaurant amenity on Caxton Street, the Roma Street Parkland and the cultural precinct are all within a few minutes on foot. For professional buyers and downsizers who have decided urban convenience is what they want, Petrie Terrace is one of a very small number of inner-city addresses that delivers it in a character-housing format rather than an apartment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Petrie Terrace</h2>
      <p>Professional buyers are the dominant segment. These are typically established professionals in their thirties and forties, often without children or with grown children, who want walkable inner-city living and have decided a heritage cottage is the right format for them. They have usually been looking through Paddington, Spring Hill, Red Hill and Petrie Terrace for months and arrive at an open home with an informed view of pricing, condition and the trade-offs between the suburbs.</p>

      <p>Downsizers from larger inner-suburban homes are a second consistent buyer group. They are typically empty-nesters who want to reduce maintenance burden, retain the character of inner-Brisbane living and gain walkability to restaurants and public space. They tend to be value-conscious but quality-conscious, and they respond particularly well to homes that have been thoughtfully renovated without losing the original character.</p>

      <p>Renovators with a strong appetite for heritage work form a smaller but persistent segment, targeting cottages where the structural bones are good but the kitchen, bathroom and outdoor areas need work. Investor activity is more limited in Petrie Terrace than in some inner-city suburbs because the entry price relative to achievable yield is no longer particularly attractive for standard cash-flow investors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Petrie Terrace</h2>
      <p>Original character matters enormously. The buyer who comes to Petrie Terrace specifically wants the heritage cottage format. VJ panelling, ceiling roses, casement windows, original fireplaces and timber floors all contribute materially to the value of a property. Homes where these features have been retained and thoughtfully restored consistently outperform comparable homes where the character has been removed in favour of a more contemporary fit-out.</p>

      <p>Usable outdoor space is the second key driver. Petrie Terrace lots are small, often around 200 to 350 square metres, and any genuinely useable outdoor area, even a well-designed rear courtyard, adds disproportionately to value. Off-street parking, where it exists, is genuinely valuable because the suburb's narrow lanes and event-day traffic from Suncorp Stadium make street parking inconsistent.</p>

      <p>Street position matters more than people often realise. The quieter lanes and dead-end streets attract a clear premium over the busier through-streets near the freeway and Caxton Street. Buyers who are sensitive to event-day noise and traffic from the stadium will pay materially more for a property positioned away from those impacts.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Petrie Terrace home for sale</h2>
      <p>Preparation should focus on showcasing the original character. Polished timber floors, restored VJ walls, original windows and any retained period detail should be visually highlighted in the campaign. A coat of paint in a warm, neutral palette that respects the period of the home does more for buyer response than a contemporary makeover that strips out the character that the buyer is actually coming here to find.</p>

      <p>The outdoor area, however small, deserves significant attention. A small courtyard that has been thoughtfully landscaped, with quality paving, mature pot plants and a sense of privacy, communicates to the buyer that this is a genuinely useable second living space rather than a leftover slab of concrete. Off-street parking should be presented clearly in the campaign because it is one of the most valuable practical features in the suburb.</p>

      <p>Because much of Petrie Terrace's housing stock is over a century old, a pre-sale building and pest inspection is a sensible investment. Stumps, roofing, electrical and termite history are all areas where minor findings are common, and addressing what is practical upfront and disclosing the rest clearly prevents a buyer's report from becoming a late-stage negotiating tool. Heritage compliance is also worth understanding before campaign: any unapproved works should be identified and addressed proactively.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Petrie Terrace</h2>
      <p>Petrie Terrace follows the broader Brisbane inner-city seasonal pattern, but the suburb's professional and downsizer buyer profile means the seasonal effect is less pronounced than in family-driven suburbs. Autumn (late February through May) is consistently a strong window: the inner-city buyer who has been looking through summer is ready to act, and the listing volume in this niche character segment is typically modest, so individual properties get clean exposure.</p>

      <p>Spring brings more listings across the broader inner city, which can create more direct competition. However, Petrie Terrace's small footprint means that listing density never reaches the levels of Paddington or Red Hill in the same season, and a well-prepared Petrie Terrace cottage will perform well in spring with the right campaign. Avoid event-heavy stadium periods in the launch week if practical, as Caxton Street and Petrie Terrace traffic can deter open-home attendance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Petrie Terrace</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Petrie Terrace cottages, correctly priced against recent comparable sales and showing original character honestly, typically sell in 25 to 40 days. Restored cottages on quiet lanes with usable outdoor space often conclude in the lower part of that range and can attract multiple registered bidders at auction. Properties that need significant work or are positioned on the busier streets near the freeway may take longer, particularly if pricing has been set above what the comparable sales support. As with every inner-city character market, pricing accuracy from launch is the single most important factor the seller controls.</p>

